Chronic pain changes you. It turns you into someone that you don‚Äôt even recognize. It makes you say and do things without even thinking because the pain just blinds you. The effort it can take to stand up and walk down stairs or even type this up is incredible. I can usually swallow it like I do with my anxiety. I hide it away because, let‚Äôs be honest, no one wants to hear that it‚Äôs week 3 and the pain isn‚Äôt going away. I find that chronic pain can sometimes be scarier than anxiety ( and trust me, that that is saying A LOT!) I never know how long the pain will stay, the extent, heck even the weather can make it better or worse. I guess what I‚Äôm saying here is that chronic pain- to me, is one of my most disabling disabilities. But it‚Äôs also the one that I hide the most. I never ever want to be known as ‚Äúthat little disabled girl‚Äù ( quoted by a dr that I no longer see due to this comment). I may be small but that does not define me. Nor does the fact that I have disabilities. I want people to judge me for my character, my love for animals and children, for my love of horses. Not by my disabilities. üí™üèæüèá‚ôøÔ∏è
